# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-england
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The **1888 British Isles tour to New Zealand and Australia** was a tour by a British rugby union team, known at the time as the "English Footballers", throughout New Zealand and Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Although a private venture not organised by any official body, this was the first major tour of the Southern Hemisphere undertaken by a European rugby team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] It paved the way for future tours by teams which are now known as British and Irish Lions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team boarded the SS Kaikoura at Gravesend on 9 March 1888, returning to England on the same ship on 11 November.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] While in Australia and New Zealand the team played a number of state, provincial, and invitation sides, but did not play any international teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] They played 35 rugby matches, winning 27, drawing 6, and losing 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Only four of the touring party had played, or would play, for their country; Seddon, Andrew Stoddart and Tom Kent for England, and Willie Thomas for Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] They also played a smaller number of Victorian rules (Australian rules) football matches, but the side had no prior experience of this before arriving in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team's legacy was honoured in 2013 when the team, along with initial captain Robert Seddon, were inducted into the World Rugby Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The team was led by England's Robert L Seddon and took in 35 games, though no test matches against international opposition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Of the games played the tourists won twenty seven, drew six and lost two matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The tour was undertaken by Shaw and Shrewsbury as a purely financial exercise with little regard to producing a "British Isles" team, and the team itself is more often recorded as an English team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The two managers were not unfamiliar with touring sides, having organised cricket teams to Australia, and the rugby tour was a follow on from the financially disastrous England Cricket tour of 1887.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The rugby tour was not an economic success either and lost both managers money.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Worse was to occur when team captain Seddon, drowned on 15 August in an accident while sculling on the Hunter River in West Maitland.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The captaincy was then passed to Andrew Stoddart a future England rugby captain and Wisden Cricketer of the Year.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] A further economic issue that related to the tour was the burgeoning professional movement that was gathering momentum in England at the time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Rugby players and clubs in Britain were divided by the growing belief that players should be paid for their time playing their sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The growing popularity of the now professional Association Football was causing many, especially in the North of England, to challenge the amateur standing of the union code.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] One of the catalysts to the split between amateur union code and the future league code, was when Jack P.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Clowes, a member of the 1888 tour, was designated a 'professional' sportsman after he accepted £15 to buy equipment shortly before he left for Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The other players on the tour were then required to sign an affidavit to state they were not to be paid for playing rugby when in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] In addition to playing 35 game of rugby union, the Lions team also played 19 games of Victorian Rules Football (later known as Australian rules football).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The Lions won 6 of the matches under the Australian rules, despite having no experience with the code prior to the tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The uniforms worn by the side on their first tour was a jersey displaying thick red, white and blue hoops, white shorts and dark socks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Two-thirds of the touring party belonged to clubs that, within a few years, would become part of the Northern Rugby Football Union, founding the game of rugby league.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Two different scoring systems were in use.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For games played in New Zealand and the Australian states of Queensland and South Australia, a try was worth one point, a conversion was worth two points and a drop goal was worth three points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For games played in New South Wales, the points values were; try - two points, conversion - three points, drop goal - four points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The points system for matches in New Zealand was one point for a try.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] On Monday, 7 May at Lancaster Park, the British played a team of Canterbury footballers in a game under Victorian Rules (Australian Rules Football).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The teams were 17-a-side rather than the twenty as was usual at the time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Players in both teams had an incomplete understanding of the rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The result of the match was a win to the British.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The points system for matches in Australia was two points for a try.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The tourists returned to Victoria for six further Victorian Rules matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] Prior to their return to Sydney, the tourists played a game under Rugby rules in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] The locals were members of the Melbourne Rugby Union Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1888-british-lions-tour-to-new-zealand-and-australia] For final preparation and selection they had played a Probables versus Possibles match on the Saturday, 28 July.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] On Saturday 28 October 1916, the former Olympic champion swimmer and the later Lord Mayor of Melbourne, Lieutenant Frank Beaurepaire, organised an Australian Rules football match in aid of the British and the French Red Cross.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Third Australian Divisional team beat the Australian Training Units Team 6.16 (52) to 4.12 (36).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The match was suggested by Sir John Monash, then in command of the 3rd Australian Division, with the complete support of Brigadier-General Sir Newton Moore, former Premier of Western Australia and, at the time, General Officer Commanding Australian Imperial Force in the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "General Monash was keen on sport for the troops", said Sir Frank.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] We had decided to play at Larkhill until the suggestion came from Sir John that we should play in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Despite not being an athlete himself, Monash firmly believed in the power of sport to boost troop morale and keep his soldiers fit for war.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "Sir John Monash, who was greeted with loud applause, said that all responsible commanders of the A.I.F. early in the war were impressed with the importance of sport, which was a powerful assistance.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Y.M.C.A. and the Australian Comforts Fund had sent liberal and adequate supplies of sporting material.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] (Hear, hear.) Every unit had its teams, and the keeping of the spirit of sport alive was an important factor in maintaining the [morale].
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] An appeal to the men that never failed was the appeal to their sportsmanship.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] (Hear, hear.) This was the inspiration which took them to many victories.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The appeal "It's up to you to play for your side" always told.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] (Cheers.) The reason the Australians were recognised, as possessing the gift for keen work to a degree not exceeded by any other army in the war, was that they had the capacity for collective effort, which was due to the influence of sport in their life in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The two generals chose Lieutenant-Colonel C.A.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Keatinge Johnson, then Commander of the A Group Training Brigade on Salisbury Plain, to be responsible for the arrangements; and, if possible, he was asked to select two first-class teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] John-Clarke, in turn, appointed Lieutenant Frank Beaurepaire — who was in the UK at the time as a commissioner of the Young Men's Christian Association (YMCA), and serving with the 3rd Division — to be responsible for the 3rd Division, and Lieutenant H.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Bartram of the 2nd Brigade, to be responsible for the 1st, 2nd, 4th, and 5th Divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Beaurepaire and Bartram immediately set to work and established an office in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The match took almost three months to organise.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] That the whole affair panned out so successfully speaks well for his organising ability.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The members of the team squads had been chosen on the basis of their footballing skills.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] That the organisers hit on the physiological [sic] moment is evidenced by a glance at the names [of the players that took part].
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] but to pick out a date on which such 36 first-class players as those who took part in the game could be brought together in London must be classed as nothing short of an inspiration.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Probably not once again during the currency of the war will such a galaxy of football talent be gathered in England at the one time . . .
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Despite their individual skills and expertise, those eventually chosen from the prospective squads to play on the day had not really been able to practice together as teams prior to the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] An Australian football match (an Australian Division v.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Training Groups) will be played at Queen's Club, West Kensington, tomorrow, at 3 p.m., in aid of the British and French Red Cross Funds.
