[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Brown, Brighton", and the Training Units' [14] "Maxfield, Fremantle", [19] "Bennett, Ballarat", and [21] "McDonald, Essendon", whose respective identification-puzzles (as of June 2022) seem impossible to resolve.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] No special sale price was fixed for the programmes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] A staff of 80 girls, each of whom carried their allocation of programmes in a basket decorated with the green and gold colours of Australia, volunteered to dispose of them, and a prize was offered for the girl whose work netted the best returns.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "[The] souvenir programmes, in aid of the French Red Cross funds sold like hot cakes, mainly because the sellers were pretty English girls.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "With donations, the game raised close on £1000 for the British and French Red Cross.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] One girl alone collected £70 from the sale of programmes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Two hand-stitched footballs were made for the match by Corporal C.C.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] McMullen, who had been a leatherworker at Henry Fordham's football factory in Sydney Road, Brunswick, prior to his enlistment in the First AIF.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Also, Fordham footballs were the official ball for the Victorian Football Association (VFA) for fourteen years in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The balls that McMullen made for the match were marked "**The AIF Ball**" on one side, and "**Match II**" on the other.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] One of the balls is currently (as of June 2022) on display at the Dandenong/Cranbourne Sub Branch of the RSL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Divisional Team played in the blue guernsey which had been made in London especially for the match, that had a large white map of Australia (minus Tasmania) on the centre of its front, and in white shorts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Training Units played in the red guernsey which had been made in London especially for the match, that had a large white kangaroo on its left breast, and in white shorts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The game was played at Queen's Club, West Kensington, on the cold, bleak, overcast, and windy late-Autumn afternoon of Saturday, 28 October 1916, before a crowd that was estimated at 3,000, by many, 5,000, by some, and as many as 6,000 by others.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] It was played over four 20-minute quarters — and, over and above those 80 minutes of elapsed playing time, the three additional breaks between the quarters meant that on such a gloomy day (sunset was at 4.42 PM) the final minutes of the match were played in very, very poor light conditions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Divisional team beat the Australian Training Units Team 6.16 (52) to 4.12 (36).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The two captains met in the centre of the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Training Unit's captain, Charlie Perry, won the toss, and chose to kick with the wind to the northern end of the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The match started off at a brisk, enthusiastic pace, with both sides competing strongly and, to the spectator's delight, displaying the game's characteristic "high marking and long kicking".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Kicking with the strong wind, with Jack Brake, Hughie James, and Les Lee "marking magnificently", and with Cyril Hoft "sparkling" on the wing, the even-less-accurate Divisional team could only kick two goals (and 8 behinds), whilst the Training Units team was restricted to just 2 behinds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Percy Jory kicked a goal with a drop-kick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] At half-time, the Divisional team was leading by 3 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The third quarter was considered to be "the best of the match".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The Training Units team, which had kicked two goals (and 2 behinds) to the Divisional team's 2 behinds, had a lead of 8 points at the three-quarter time interval.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] As the match progressed it was becoming increasingly obvious that the match fitness of the players (or the absence thereof), and not just the strong wind favouring one end of the ground, would play a large part in the final result of the match (Richardson, 2016, p.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] In 1937, Dan Minogue recalled that, "the match was played on a Saturday afternoon.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The soldiers who had taken part in it had leave in London till Sunday night.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The admission charges to the match were 1/-, 2/6 and 10/-.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Overall, the accurate, interesting, and matter-of-fact press reports of the exhibition match (collectively) provided a strong and long-overdue contrast to what Richardson usefully identifies (at 2016, p.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] 307) as the "misguided mythology" that was ever so firmly embedded in the questionable characterisation — echoing the widely quoted sentiments of Henry Newbolt's poem *Vitaï Lampada* — made early in the war, of the Australian "digger" as a fierce footballer playing on another field.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "Whether footballers or the authorities controlling the game in Victoria could not do more towards "Winning the War" than they are doing is a matter about which opinions differ, but that they have done their share in providing recruits is beyond doubt.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] After all, this is only what it should be.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Owing to the training necessary to become an expert (and everyone aspires to be an expert), and the physical fitness and endurance required to take part in a game of football, our players should, and, from letters received, do, make the best soldiers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] From all sides one hears glowing accounts of their discipline, ability to do long marches, and quickness and resource in dangers and difficulties.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Beyond this, the match had quite a different significance for various sorts of individuals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The various press reports also reflected a wide range of different motivations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] However, it was not until the match between the RAAF and HMAS Shropshire, at Hyde Park, London, organised by ex-Collinwood footballer and later ANFC secretary Bruce Andrew, that a second exhibition match was held in the UK.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] A third match, contested between RAAF HQ (captain, Bruce Andrew) and the RAAF's No.10 (Sunderland) Squadron (captain, Jack Forrest), took place, soon after, at Hyde Park on 8 January 1944.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] In late September 1916, it was announced in the Australian press that "General Monash has granted a holiday [to his troops] for an exhibition of Australian football arranged to take place in London, early in October".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] A week before the match, the Australian press noted that, "Australian soldiers are introducing Australian football into Britain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The captain of the third division team is Lieutenant B.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Sloss, of South Melbourne, and the captain of the training groups team is Captain W.H.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "An Australian football match was played on the Queens Club ground, London, on Saturday, between teams representing the Australian 3rd Division, and the Australian trainees at Salisbury Plain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] the small number that did provide a match report, only supplied (at the most) a two paragraph description of the match itself, and failed to supply any detailed list of participants.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Ten weeks later (20 December 1916), Brosnan's second article not only contained a detailed first-person account of the events of the day from *The Winner's* London-based correspondent, E.A.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Bland, but, also, Bland's description of first-time spectators' impressions of Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Brosnan's article, which supplied a photograph of each team (i.e., **[ADP.3]**, and **[TUP.3]**), also included extensive extracts taken directly from the four major British sporting papers, *Sporting Life*, *The Sportsman*, *The Times*, and *The Weekly Despatch*.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The reports that appeared in the New Zealand press took the form of brief, simple news items.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The contents of an entirely different fifth article (apparently written on 29 October 1916), taken from *The Referee* of London, was published in *The (Emerald Hill) Record* of 6 January 1917.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The British reports concentrated on the match as an event, rather than a contest; and were, thus, devoid of the normal sorts of descriptions of the patterns of play, the performance of prominent individuals, particular match incidents, and the progression of the scores.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Consequently, they tended to focus on the absence of the "off-side" rule, kicking long drop-kicks, and kicking long and accurate place-kicks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "Those who had the good fortune to witness the match will be in agreement that it is a most exhilarating and exciting pastime, and it is played at such a pace throughout that it is unquestionably the fastest outdoor game, with the exception of lacrosse.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The ball, it should be mentioned, is slightly larger than the Rugby ball, but similar in shape, with the ends more flattened.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Some of the players showed wonderful control, in their punches, and also in their kicking, but more noticeable, perhaps, than either was the high marking, players leaping in the air to make a fair catch from a pass, and this entitled them to a kick in any direction.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "Long kicking and marking are two of the distinctive features.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] When the ball is caught from a clean kick of over ten yards the player is entitled to a free kick in any direction.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] If the angle is favorable he tries to drop or punt a goal, but if badly placed he endeavors to kick to a fellow player.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] There is much keen competition in jumping in the air to make a catch, and in this phase are very expert.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The game is very fast, very open, very spectacular, and needs plenty of stamina and pace.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The ruck men and rovers are required to be up and doing all the time, and on account of the strain they are changed and given fixed positions every quarter.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] There is also plenty of work for the field umpire who requires to be very quick to keep up with the play.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "One thing that is clearly apparent is the enormous amount of skill which is required, while physical fitness is also essential.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] There can be no doubt of it being a game of high value from an athletic point of view.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] As a spectacle, much can be said in its favor, for the fluctuations are rapid, brought about by the nimbleness, versatility, and dexterity of the players. . . .
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Pace is an important essential, but a still greater feature is high marking and long kicking.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] It is no unusual thing for several players to spring between 4ft. and 5ft. in the air to catch the ball from a kick over ten yards, which constitutes a mark and entitles the successful player to a free kick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] Drop-kicking and place kicking are further salient points, and these reach a remarkably high standard for accuracy and length.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] "Football — Australian fashion — drew a big crowd to Queen's Club yesterday afternoon, when a team chosen from the Third Division beat the representatives of the Combined Training Groups by 52 points to 36.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] It was the first time that the fast Australian game had ever been played by skilled exponents in London, and the onlookers could be readily grouped in two classes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] There were the partisans in slouched bats over hard-bitten Anzac faces, who had come to "barrack" for or against the "Fighting Third", the only Anzac Division which has not yet seen active service.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] There were also curious sportsmen and sportswomen of all kinds, who had come out to get a glimpse of the game of which so much has been written here at one time and another. . . .
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] The spectators were also treated to their first exhibition of Australian "barracking".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] This barracking is a cheerful running comment, absolutely without prejudice, on the players, the spectators, the referee, the line umpires, and lastly the game itself.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] On Saturday it was mostly concerned with references to the military history of the teams engaged.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] When a catch was missed, for instance, a shrill and penetrating voice inquired of the abashed player "D'you think it's a bomb?
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p01] On 19 November 1916, the *New York Times* published a photograph, taken during the match, of a large pack of players contesting for a mark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] A film (**[NR.1]**) was taken at the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] A remastered and colourised version (**[NR.2]**) of the original film was released in 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] Two official photographs were taken of each team prior to the match by the same photographer.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] "Writing from the Y.M.C.A.'s quarters at 21 Bartholomew road, London, to Mr E.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] It was, as you are probably aware, a pioneer game of first class Australian football, and went off well indeed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] I had the honor of suggesting the game, and arranging much of the detail, particularly in the early stages.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] You will see me seated in uniform next to Dan Minogue, Vice-Captain, and Bruce Sloss, Captain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] Third Division won by 6 goals 16 behinds, to 4 goals 12 behinds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] The mounting boards of the souvenir sets were decorated with a British Union Jack and an Australian Red Ensign, with "Australian Football in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] 1916" at their head, and "Organizer of Match & Donor of Photos to Club Lieut.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1916-pioneer-exhibition-game-p02] They were mounted especially for presentation by the *Allan Studio*, of 318 Smith Street, Collingwood.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The **1972 Carlton Football Club season** was the Carlton Football Club's 109th season of competition, and 76th as a member of the Victorian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Carlton fielded teams in the senior, reserves and under-19s grades of the 1972 VFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Under captain-coach John Nicholls, who assumed the coaching role this season after the departure of dual-premiership coach Ron Barassi at the end of 1971, Carlton won the VFL minor and major premierships, defeating Richmond in the Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] It was the 11th senior VFL premiership in the club's history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Following the VFL season, Carlton competed in the Championship of Australia tournament, finishing runner-up to the SANFL's North Adelaide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The club then embarked upon a world tour, playing three exhibition matches overseas against an Australian All-Stars team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The 1972 VFL season was the 76th season of the VFL competition since its inception in 1897; and, having competed in every season, it was also the 76th season contested by the Carlton Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] As it had been since 1897, the club's home ground was Princes Park in North Carlton; additionally, it was standard for all clubs in the league at the time to play three or four matches per year at the neutral VFL Park in Mulgrave.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In addition to its senior team, Carlton fielded teams in both the VFL reserves and under-19s competitions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] George Harris continued as club president through 1972, a position he had held since after the 1964 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Following the 1971 season, Ron Barassi stepped down as coach; at the time, he left to focus on his business career, although he ultimately returned to VFL coaching (at North Melbourne) after only a year.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Barassi had coached Carlton for seven seasons, and led the team to two senior premierships: 1968 and 1970.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] John Nicholls, who had been captain since mid-1968, took on Barassi's former role to become captain-coach.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The following is the final senior squad as announced at the start of the 1972 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Numbers in parentheses represent games played and goals kicked for Carlton in the 1972 VFL premiership season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Only supplementary players who played a senior match during the season are listed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The following summarises player transfers to and from the club between the conclusion of the 1971 season and the conclusion of the 1972 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Carlton played three practice matches during March 1972 – including, as it turned out, matches against both of the teams it would face in Grand Finals later in the year: Richmond and North Adelaide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Carlton finished the home-and-away season as the minor premiers in 1972, with a win–loss record of 18–3–1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The team sat as low as 6th after Round 4 with a record of 2–1–1, but lost only two of its remaining eighteen matches for the season, moving up to and holding first place from Round 12 until the end of the season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Two of Carlton's three losses were by fewer than six points; a 31-point loss against Richmond in Round 14 was the worst performance of the home-and-away season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Despite the strong performance, Carlton was in a constant fight for the minor premiership with Richmond, who finished with a record of 18–4–0.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Richmond drew within half a game of Carlton after beating them in Round 14; both teams then won all of their remaining eight matches, maintaining that half-game margin until the end of the season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Carlton came very close to losing the minor premiership in the final round, eventually beating Footscray by three points with the significant assistance of Footscray's inaccurate goalkicking .
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Under the new McIntyre Final Five, Carlton had a bye in the first week of finals, before playing qualifying final winner Richmond in the second semi-final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In a low-scoring match, Carlton held Richmond to only one goal in the first half, but Richmond was able to fight back and level the scores at 8.13 (61); Alex Jesaulenko had an unlikely set shot from 70m after the final siren to attempt win the game, but did not make the distance.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The match was replayed the following weekend, and Carlton suffered its heaviest loss of the season, by 41 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In the preliminary final against St Kilda, Carlton overcome an 11-point half-time deficit to win by 16 points, and to progress to the Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Entering the Grand Final, Richmond was the strong favourite, with bookmakers offering odds of 1–2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Richmond had a record of 11–0–1 from its last twelve games, and had a record of 3–0–1 in its four games against Carlton for the season, including inflicting Carlton's heaviest two losses.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Some commentators thought Carlton was impressive enough against St Kilda to be a chance at winning, but most tipped Richmond for the premiership.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In an unprecedentedly high scoring game, Carlton kicked eight goals in the first quarter and ten in the second quarter to set up a match-winning 45-point lead by half-time, which Richmond never challenged; Carlton ultimately won by 27 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In a strong display from its forwards, Alex Jesaulenko kicked seven goals, and Robert Walls and John Nicholls kicked six each.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The 1972 Championship of Australia series was played on the weekend following the VFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The tournament was held at the Adelaide Oval, with two semi-finals played on the Saturday, and the final and third-place playoff on the Sunday.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The tournament was contested by the premiers of the four state leagues: Carlton (VFL), North Adelaide (SANFL), East Perth (WANFL), and City-South (from the NTFA, winner of the Tasmanian State Premiership).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The prize for the winning team was $10,000.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Carlton easily accounted for East Perth in its semi-final, a rough game from which several East Perth players earned suspensions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Grand final against North Adelaide was a close contest; Carlton held a two-goal lead after five minutes of the final quarter, but did not score again and was overrun by North Adelaide by one point.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In October and November, Carlton and a team of All-Stars embarked upon a world tour, playing three exhibition matches in different countries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Carlton premiership twenty was as below.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] From 22 October until 13 November, the Carlton team went on a three-week world tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The tour was organised during the season by president George Harris.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] In addition to a busy social calendar, the tour featured three exhibition matches between Carlton and a team of All-Stars from other senior teams around Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] When initially organised, the tour was to have featured matches at: The Oval in London, UK; on a temporary field in Stuttgart, West Germany; and at Lenin Stadium in Moscow, USSR – however, of these, only the London match went ahead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Moscow match was abruptly cancelled by the Soviet Union, which cited "technical reasons" in its communication to the Australian embassy; Harris arranged for the Russian leg of the tour to instead be played in Athens, Greece.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Stuttgart match was then cancelled when it became apparent that an early winter would render the match unplayable; Harris organised for this leg of the tour to be played in Singapore.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The All-Stars team which accompanied Carlton on the tour was announced in July.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Twenty-two players were selected, each from a different club: eleven came from the other eleven VFL clubs, five came from SANFL clubs, five came from WAFL clubs and one came from Tasmania.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The first match was played as originally scheduled at The Oval in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] A purpose-built cricket venue, The Oval was an appropriate size and shape for Australian rules football; the hard centre wicket area was covered over with coir mats for the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Prince of Wales (now Charles III) was in attendance at the match, and met with the touring party prior to the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The match drew a crowd of approximately 9,000 people, almost all of whom were Australian expatriates.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The second match in Athens was the most bizarre of the tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] This resulted in a high-scoring match, the All-Stars winning 19.13 (127) to 19.10 (124); Robert Walls kicked ten goals for Carlton and David Clarke kicked nine for the All-Stars.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The attendance of 3,000 was described as being similar in size to that drawn by a midweek soccer match in Athens at the time, and the Greek crowd reportedly supported Carlton because its guernsey matched the Greek national colours of blue and white.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The final match in Singapore was played on a temporary oval field, which was set up on three adjacent soccer pitches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The crowd of 8,500 was mostly a mixture of locals and Australian servicemen based in Singapore.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The oppressively humid weather was the most significant difficulty with the match, which was won by the All-Stars, 11.11 (77) to 9.11 (65).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Laws in Singapore at the time prevented men from wearing long hair, so many players on both teams were forced to have haircuts before the tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Upon return, Harris announced that the club intended to return to Europe for a second tour in 1973, including another match at The Oval, a rescheduled match in Stuttgart, as well as matches in Wales and Ireland; but, the second tour never went ahead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The most notable absence from the premiership twenty was that of full forward Greg Kennedy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Kennedy was the club's leading goalkicker for the season, and had played 22 matches; but he had kicked only one goal in each of the semi-finals against Richmond.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Kennedy was replaced as 20th man by Garry Crane; Jesaulenko kicked seven goals from full-forward in the Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Full forward Greg Kennedy was Carlton's leading goalkicker, in his first season of VFL football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Aged 22 at the start of the season, Kennedy was zoned to Carlton from Eaglehawk, after he kicked 139 goals and won the Michelsen Medal as Bendigo Football League best and fairest in 1971.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] He kicked 76 goals in 22 VFL premiership matches, and a further three goals in the Championship of Australia matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] It was the only time that Kennedy led Carlton's goalkicking in the three seasons he spent with the club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Robert Reynolds Trophy for Carlton's senior best and fairest was awarded to Geoff Southby.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] It was the second consecutive time Southby had won the award, in only his second year at the club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Vin Catoggio, who played both under 19s and reserves football for Carlton during the season, was a joint-winner of the Morrish Medal, for the under 19s league best-and-fairest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Catoggio polled 23 votes to tie for the award with Ian Kilmartin (North Melbourne).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Crane, who played in the reserves while recovering from injury for much of the season, polled three Brownlow votes and ten Gardiner votes to win the award.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Three Carlton players represented the winning Victorian team in the 1972 Perth Carnival, which was held from 17 to 24 June at Subiaco Oval during the split Round 12 of the VFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] Jesaulenko was selected in the All-Australian Team at the conclusion of the Carnival.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Carlton reserves team finished third out of twelve teams, losing in the preliminary final against Hawthorn.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] After an average start to the season, the reserves team won its last eight home-and-away matches to finish fifth on the ladder with a record of 14–8, only just reaching the final five.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1972-carlton-football-club-season] The Under 19s failed to reach the final five.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] The **1997 AFL season** was the 101st season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] The season ran from 27 March until 27 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top eight clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] Before the season, the Port Adelaide Football Club (SANFL) was admitted to the league, increasing the South Australian membership to two clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] Foundation club Fitzroy, which had gone into administration in 1996, merged with the Brisbane Bears to form a new Queensland-based team known as the Brisbane Lions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] The Footscray Football Club changed its name to the Western Bulldogs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] With these changes, the league's size remained at sixteen clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] The premiership was won by the Adelaide Football Club for the first time, after it defeated St Kilda by 31 points in the 1997 AFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in green indicate that the team finished the round inside the top 8.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in blue indicates the team finished first on the ladder in that round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/1997-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in red indicates the team finished in last place on the ladder in that round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2005-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The **2005 EU Cup** of Australian rules football was held in London (England) on 9 October 2005, with 10 national teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2005-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The tournament was won by Belgium who were crowned European Champions after defeating Sweden in the final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2016-afl-europe-championship] The **2016 AFL Europe Championship** was an 18-a-side Australian rules football competition held in London, United Kingdom between European countries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2016-afl-europe-championship] This was the third AFL Europe Championship, run by AFL Europe.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2016-afl-europe-championship] Matches were played at Motspur Park in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2016-afl-europe-championship] Contested between four national teams, the Championships were won by Great Britain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The **2019 AFL Women's season** was the third season of the AFL Women's (AFLW) competition, the highest-level senior women's Australian rules football competition in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The season featured ten clubs and ran from 2 February to 31 March, comprising a seven-round home-and-away season followed by a two-week finals series featuring the top two clubs from each conference.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Australian Football League (AFL) clubs Geelong and North Melbourne featured for the first time in 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Adelaide won the premiership, defeating Carlton by 45 points in the 2019 AFL Women's Grand Final; it was Adelaide's second AFL Women's premiership.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Adelaide's Erin Phillips won her second AFL Women's best and fairest award as the league's best and fairest player, and teammate Stevie-Lee Thompson won the AFL Women's leading goalkicker award as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Two new teams, Geelong and North Melbourne, joined the competition, bringing the total number of teams to ten.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The North Melbourne team has a strong Tasmanian focus; some players were based in Tasmania and some home games were held in the state.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The introduction of the new teams was the first stage of a two-year expansion that took the league to fourteen teams for the 2020 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Despite the introduction of new teams, the league retained a seven-round home-and-away season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] This was achieved by splitting the competition into two conferences.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Each team play four games against their fellow conference members and three "cross-over" matches against teams from the other conference.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Conference membership was based on the final ladder positions of the 2018 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The finals series was expanded to include preliminary finals for the first time; the two teams who finish the highest in each conference at the end of the home-and-away season qualified for the preliminary finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The winners of these games played in the AFL Women's Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The make-up of the conferences, along with the fixture, was released in October 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The conference system proved controversial as the teams in Conference A consistently outplayed the teams on Conference B, resulting in the first, second, fifth and sixth best overall teams making the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] Due to the conference system, as of 2024, this remains the only season where the North Melbourne team did not make the finals (despite a 5-2 record).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] There were 11 rule changes brought in for the 2019 AFLW season (three AFLW specific).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/2019-aflw-season] The full fixture and make-up of the conferences was released on 26 October 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In England, Australian rules football is a team and spectator sport with a long history.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] It is home to the longest-running Australian rules fixture outside Australia: the match between Oxford and Cambridge Universities which has been contested annually since 1923.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] All other current competitions originated in 1989 with the founding of what is now AFL London, the longest-running Australian rules football league in Europe.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The current governing body, AFL England, was formed in 2012 and expanded the game in 2018 to include the additional regional divisions: AFL Central & Northern England and AFL Southern England.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The sport's origins are said to be in England, specifically public school football games.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Several of the sport's founders were born and educated there including J.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Thompson, William Hammersley and James Bryant, while Tom Wills—held by many as the sport's founder—was educated at and played rugby with the Rugby School.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However, it struggled for decades to establish roots given the dominance of traditional football codes in rugby football and the growing popularity of soccer.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Nevertheless, it was one of the first countries outside of Australia where the game was played in the 1880s and to host regular competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Australian Football League (AFL) exhibition matches were held at The Oval in London semi-annually between 1986 and 2006 (the last standalone event was held in 2012) and were well attended, with attendances ranging from 4,500 to a record of 18,884 in 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] England rarely competes in a standalone team, and it is typically represented along with Scotland and Wales as the Great Britain team at the Australian Football International Cup (best result 6th) and AFL Europe Championship (2 titles).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However, an English side has competed in several standalone tests and has been successful at the Euro Cup with 5 titles.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Nevertheless, London has hosted several internationals, including the 2001 Atlantic Alliance Cup, the 2005 and 2015 EU Cups, and the 2016 and 2019 AFL Europe Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] English-born players have been successful at the sport's highest level in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In the AFL, Bill Eason has the most games (220) and most goals (187).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In the AFL Women's, Sabrina Frederick has the most games and goals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] , founder of Australian Football, was singled out in the national press for his prowess on the football field at the Rugby School in the 1850s.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] According to the AFL, the sport's origins were in England with public school football games being adopted by Australians in the 1850s leading to the creation of what is now known as Australian Football in Melbourne in the British Colony of Victoria in 1859.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Several of the sport's founders were English including J.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Thompson, William Hammersley and James Bryant, with Tom Wills having been educated at and played rugby football with the Rugby School.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Even Wills, who favoured many rules of Rugby School football, saw the need for compromise.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] While the game found its way to Ireland in the 1870s and there was also some awareness in England of the popularity of the game in Australia, it was not established locally until much later.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] This is primarily due to the growing popularity of locally developing football codes including rugby football and later British Association (soccer) which, like Australian Football, were also developing from public school football games.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The English were also heavily involved in the development of the code in the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] James Henry Gardiner founded the North Melbourne Football Club in 1869 which was later instrumental to unifying football rules in the Colony of Tasmania.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] John Acraman and Richard Twopeny were the key players in establishing it in the Colony of South Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Between 1870 and World War I, many overseas students studied medicine in Scotland, and some went down to England to play the Australian Rules teams in that country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] A Lancashire paper from 1881 mentions a local initiative to introduce "Victorian Rules Football" to England as an alternative to rugby and Association football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Harrison, then known as the "father of Australian Football", visited London where he proposed unifying Australian rules with Rugby under a set of hybrid rules and suggested that rugby clubs adopt some of the Victorian Rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] English football officials expressed their insult at the suggestion that they "abandon their rules to oblige an Antipodean game".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Nevertheless, when first proposing a football tour of Australia and New Zealand in March 1887, James Lillywhite, Alfred Shaw and Arthur Shrewsbury posited that the best way to ensure the success of the venture would be to play under the Australian rules where the sport was most popular.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Australians studying at Edinburgh University and London University formed teams and competed in London in 1888.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Spurred on by the upcoming English football team's tour of Australia, a scratch match between Edinburgh Australians and London Australians was planned to be held at Balham on 14 April 1888.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However the match was postponed citing lack of player numbers and suitability of the venue.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] It was finally played on 26 May 1888 at Balham, London won 4 goals to 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] There was little interest in the match outside of the Australian expat community.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However the game was poorly organised and the selected ground was so out of the way that most spectators failed to find it, proving to be lost opportunity to promote the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] A return match was played on the same ground on the 30th May resulting in a draw.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match drew considerable praise in UK newspapers such as the *Times* and the *Scotsman*.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Australian rules football was played by a British representative rugby team which toured Australia in 1888.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The team arrived in Hobart, Tasmania on 18 April.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] They attended a social function with the Southern Tasmanian Football Association, before going to New Zealand for a series of rugby matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] After they returned to Australia they again trained in Australian rules in Sydney, before leaving for Victoria in mid-June.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] They played against several of the stronger football clubs from Melbourne including the Carlton Football Club, South Melbourne Football Club, Essendon Football Club, Fitzroy Football Club and Port Melbourne Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The team also played against several of the stronger South Australian teams, including South Adelaide Football Club, Port Adelaide Football Club, Adelaide Football Club (no connection to the later Adelaide club), Norwood Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The only club from outside of Victoria or South Australia which played against them was the Maitland Football Club (from the Hunter Valley in New South Wales).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The British team won six matches, including a win over Port Adelaide at Adelaide Oval on 10 July 1888, and drew one.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The reigning Victorian premiers, Carlton defeated Great Britain at the MCG 14.17 to 3.8.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] At this stage goals and points were recorded but only goals counted in the score; for example, when Great Britain played Castlemaine under very heavy conditions they kicked 1 goal 2 points and the locals kicked 1 goal 4 points, but the match was declared a draw.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Great Britain also played 35 games of rugby, making a total of 54 games in 21 weeks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] A star of the team's Australian rules games was Andrew Stoddart, who captained the team for part of its tour and also captained England in cricket.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The 1888 tour had been organised by the English cricketer Arthur Shrewsbury but his involvement with Australian Rules football did not end there.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] He planned to have an Australian team sent to the United Kingdom to play a series of demonstration matches and to that end he looked to Scotland where he had identified possible opponents.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Shrewsbury's plans are outlined in his correspondence with Alfred Shaw and Turner, the Nottingham Cricket Club Secretary.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Shrewsbury suggested that the 'Edinburgh Australians' team at Edinburgh University should travel down to England to meet the Australian team in a series of demonstration matches in Lancashire and Yorkshire.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Unfortunately his bold plan did not eventuate as the authorities in Australia aborted the venture and a possible expansion of Australian Rules in the UK was lost.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1894, a dramatic costume football match was played at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground involving prominent English celebrities Jennie Lee, Wallace Brownlow and Harry Musgrove.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] There were reports from Australia that the game was being played in England between two clubs in 1903 and in 1904.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] By 1906 there were three clubs holding regular competition two of which were in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The Oxford University Australian Rules Football Club was founded in 1906.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] As early as 1911 the game was being played regularly at Oxford.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The Cambridge University Australian Rules Football Club is believed to have been founded around 1911.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1911 Oxford University captained by Alfred Clemens defeated Cambridge University captained by Ron Larking 13.9 (87) to 5.12 (42).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1914, H C A Harrison reported that the game was being played regularly at both Oxford and Cambridge universities though few records exist of contests between 1911 and 1921.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1915 a Victoria vs South Australia match was played at Portland Canteen ground at Weymouth, Dorset.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match drew a large crowd and significant press coverage.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1917 HMAS *Australia*'s Australian Football team played against a team of soldiers in London which drew significant attendance and interest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In November 1917, the Australian army and navy played a rugby match against each other in London, however the seconds played a match under Australian rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] As a celebration of Australia Day January 1918, a match was held at Cambridge between London Headquarters and Australian Cadets, with London winning 80 to 63.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However, the end of World War I saw the game outside of the universities go into hiatus.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] After the war, in 1921, the Oxford University–Cambridge University Varsity match between expatriate Australian students became an annual contest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] This game is still played, and it is the longest-running Australian rules fixture outside Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match is an official Varsity competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Over the years, some distinguished Australians to have played in the match include Mike Fitzpatrick, Chris Maxwell, Joe Santamaria, Sir Rod Eddington and Andrew Michelmore.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The AIF played a match in 1940 between the "Impossibles" and the "Improbables".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] When the RMS *Moreton Bay* returned to England after 1941 it played in advertised matches at Portsmouth.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] RAAF (Sunderland) vs RAF Mount Batten was played in 1943 in Plymouth.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In November of the same year, a game was played in Sussex between No.11 Personnel despatch and Reception centre team based in Brighton vs RAAF Headquarters from London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Teams representing RAAF, Headquarters vs Sunderland, met in Hyde Park in 1944 in front of a sizeable crowd.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1945, HMAS *Australia* defeated RAAF at Dulwich 11.12 to 10.5.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1948, Australia's champion axemen team announced its plans to introduce Australian rules football into England.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1952, a match was played at Rosslyn Park F.C. in South West London between HMAS *Vengeance* and English-Australians ("the Wombats").
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The Wombats also organised a match at Cambridge.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1967, Australian expatriates including Michael Cyril Hall and Ted Ford attempted to organise Australian Football in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Ted engaged high-profile expatriate Australians including Rolf Harris, Alan Freeman, Barry Humphries, Neil Hawke, Keith Miller and former Australian prime minister Sir Robert Menzies to support the venture and raise publicity for it.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Ford organised a charity match was played in Regent's Park in London, between local club Kensington Demons and established out of town club Oxford University.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Athol Guy (who had played VFL reserves with St Kilda) also made a special appearance as a player.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match also featured England's first all-women's match between Aussie Girls and Wild Colonial Girls as a curtain raiser.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match attracted a crowd of 1,000 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] A follow-up match between Earl's Court Magpies and Australian Dentists attracted 700 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] By May 7 established local teams were ready to form a local league these teams included: Australian Dentists, Australian Navy, Oxford University, Cambridge University, Kensington Demons, Earls Court Magpies and London House.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In July, Royal Australian Navy (RAN) personnel played against a combined side drawn from the Earls Court Magpies; Kensington Demons and Australian Dentists in front of a crowd of 1,200 at Regent's Park.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] RAN personnel would go on to play against local school sides and local rugby clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] After some time finding its roots, the Australian National Football League (UK) was formed which by 1970 had six teams, Victorians; Rest of Australia; Portsmouth Naval Base; Plymouth Naval Base; London Gaelic Football Club and Hampstead Rugby Club with matches played in the summer.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The later inclusion of two English rugby sides was helping them keep fit in the off-season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Later clubs to play in the league included the Kensington Demons, Earls Court Magpies, Oxford University Blues, Australian Dentists and Australian Navy (based in Portsmouth).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1972, the first exhibition match of the VFL was played at The Oval in London as part of the Carlton Football Club 1972 preseason World Tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The match attracted 9,000 in a carnival-like atmosphere.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] However, the arrival of the spectacle of elite-level VFL also saw the end of the game at the grassroots in England with no further organised competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Between 1987 and 2006, VFL/AFL exhibition matches had become an almost annual event, but the only game since then being in 2012.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] With a large number of ex-patriate Australians, interest in the game grew, and small crowds of up to 10,000 were in attendance for the event in some years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Interest and crowds grew further with the change of the VFL to the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Highlights during this time included large crowds for and Australian Football League match between West Coast Eagles and Collingwood in 1997, with an attendance of about 14,000, and a match between Richmond and Essendon in 2002 that drew about 13,000.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 1989, the British Australian rules football League (BARFL) was formed by John Jelly, Andrew Zweck, Steve Poulsen and others.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] One of the key people in the establishment of the competition was former professional Australian player Darren Ogier, who helped introduce a balancing rule whereby at least half of the club's on-field players must be non-Australian.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] As the competition became more popular, results were reported in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] From 1992, the AFL began contributing AUD $6,000 a year to the league; however, it withdrew its financial contributions in 1994, expressing a preference for grants to be spent on junior programs and school projects instead of the senior competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Despite the lack of AFL support, local BARFL Grand Finals become a large event attracting attendances in the thousands, including a record crowd of 1,500 in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 2002 a national team represented Great Britain at the Australian Football International Cup for the first time, finishing the tournament in 6th place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] 2005 saw the British Bulldogs again compete in the International Cup, again finishing 6th overall.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Following the 2005 International Cup, promising 22-year-old British Bulldog Luke Matias began playing with the Port Melbourne Football Club in the Victorian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Also in 2005, the first Western Derby to be played outside of Australia, the West Coast Eagles v.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Fremantle game was played as a pre-season test at The Oval in London, drawing a record crowd of 18,884.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 2005 the first junior development program, Aussie Rules Schools, commenced.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The program, co-ordinated by the new development body Aussie Rules UK, part of Aussie Rules International was kicked off.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] This project has seen up to 10 English schools adopt Aussie Rules as part of the school curriculum to combat obesity.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Juniors teams have competed at the London Youth Games.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] 2006 was a big year for Aussie Rules in England, with the admission of new clubs in Manchester, Middlesbrough and Thanet.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] On 17 September 2006 history was made in Denmark when the England Dragonslayers took on the Denmark Vikings in Europe's first fully-fledged international junior Aussie Rules match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] England claimed the King Canute Cup, with England 6.10(46) defeating Denmark 0.6(6).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In July 2007, the AFL announced that the annual London exhibition match was likely to be abandoned for the year, after only the Western Bulldogs had expressed interest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In a first in 2007, the GB Bulldogs including several past and future England players, soundly defeated Ireland in Dublin 11.15(81) to 2.9(21).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 2008, a resolution to the divide between the two competing leagues saw a single national body, AFL Britain form, which formally affiliated to the AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The BARFL was dissolved and became AFL London, while regional leagues including the Scottish Australian Rules Football League and the Welsh Australian Rules Football League affiliated with the new national body.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 2012, AFL England was formed as the national governing body for Australian rules football in England, separate to AFL Scotland and AFL Wales.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] In 2004, there were a total of around 435 senior players across 18 clubs in England.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The local league has a higher number of ex-patriate Australians compared to other countries that participate in the sport, however the league recently put in place caps on the number of expatriate players in certain divisions to improve the mix and encourage more local players.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] By the end of 2007, the game had experienced substantial growth due to the placement of permanent development officers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Australian rules football is regularly shown on TNT Sports.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] AFL England currently manages four national teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The Great Britain Bulldogs and Great Britain Swans compete every three years at the International Cup in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The squad is made up of players mainly from the London clubs, however they are often joined by players competing in Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] The English teams are known as the England Dragonslayers and the England Vixens.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-england/australian-rules-football-in-england] Both teams won the AFL Europe Euro Cup in 2017.
